[2] Chronology, selected issues since Feb 2006
Date: Wed, 31 Jan 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters [edited]
<http://today.reuters.com/News/CrisesArticle.aspx?storyId=L31246823>

A Nigerian woman who died of flu symptoms has tested positive for the H5N1
bird flu virus, Information Minister Frank Nweke said on Wednesday, [31 Jan
2007], the first reported death from the virus in the West African country.
Here is a brief chronology of some of the major bird flu developments:
8 Feb 2006 -- The 1st African cases of the deadly H5N1 strain are detected
in poultry in the northern Nigerian states of Kano, Kaduna and Plateau.
17 Feb 2006 -- Egypt finds its first cases of H5N1 in chickens.
18 Feb, 2006 -- India announces its first cases of H5N1, finding the virus
in poultry in a western state.
25 Feb 2006 -- France confirms H5N1 at a farm in the east where thousands
of turkeys have died. It is the 1st case of the virus in domestic farm
birds in the EU.
8 Aug 2006 -- China says its 1st H5N1 human case was in 2003, and not in
2005 as it had originally reported.
28 Sep 2006 -- China shares long-sought-after samples of H5N1 in what many
scientists view as a breakthrough in cooperation.
8 Dec 2006 -- Foreign donors pledge an additional $475.9 million for the
global fight against the virus at the end of a 3-day meeting in Mali.
2 Dec 2006 -- South Korea confirms a 4th case of bird flu in poultry. In
November, South Korea had confirmed its 1st case of H5N1 in about 3 years.
9 Jan 2007 - China announces that a farmer from the eastern province of
Anhui contracted H5N1 in December, the country's first human case in
months. He was released from hospital on 6 Jan 2007.
15 Jan 2007 -- Thailand reports its first outbreak of H5N1 in 6 months in
some ducks in the northern province of Phitsanulok.
16 Jan 2007 -- Japan confirms its first outbreak of H5N1 in 3 years in
poultry in the southwestern prefecture of Miyazaki. A 2nd outbreak is
confirmed on Jan 27.
29 Jan 2007 - WHO confirms another death in Indonesia. The global death
toll stands at 164.
31 Jan 2007 -- Nigeria says that a woman from the commercial capital Lagos
is the 1st confirmed human victim of bird flu in sub-Saharan Africa. Test
samples are being sent to foreign laboratories for further confirmation.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A WHO map, titled "World: Areas reporting confirmed occurrence of H5N1
avian influenza in poultry and wild birds since 1 Jan 2007, status as of 25
Jan 2007 (latest available update)," is available at
<http://gamapserver.who.int/mapLibrary/Files/Maps/Global_SubNat_H5N1inAnimalConfirmed_2007_20070125.png>.
The recent outbreak in Russia (Krasnodar) is not yet included. - Mod.AS]
